* ###  **THIS PROBLEM IS A VERY CLASSICAL PROBLEM OF DP**
**EXPLANATION:**
1. **`THE IDEA IS VERY VERY SIMPLE, IF YOU UNDERSTAND THE RECURSIVE CODE LOGIC THEN, CONVERT IT INTO DP IS CAKEWALK !!! :)`**

1. **`IN THIS PROBLEM WE'RE GIVEN A TWO STRINGS "Word1" && "Word2". WE NEED TO CONVERT FIRST STRING TO SECOND, WITH THE HELP OF THREE OPERATIONS (INSERT, DELETE, REPLACE)..`**

1. **`STEP 1: WHEN BOTH CHARACTERS OF STRING MATCHES WE DO NOT HAVE TO DO ANYTHING (ANY OPERATIONS). JUST SIMPLY RECURR FOR NEXT ELEMENTS IN BOTH STRINGS`!**
1. **`STEP 2: WHEN CHARACTERS DOESN'T MATCH, WE NEED TO DO THREE OPERATIONS THAT IS`:**
        **`a) INSERT :  editDist(w1, w2, n, m - 1) :- Decrement second string size, cuz we have to insert character according to second string`** 
        **`b) DELETE :  editDist(w1, w2, n - 1, m) :- Decrement first string size, cuz we to convert first string to second string =, by deleting characters`** 
        **`c) REPLACE : editDist(w1, w2, n - 1, m - 1) :- Again, decrement Both string size, cuz let assume we replaced the character of second string with the character                                                    of first string. Hence, both characters are same again.`**  
1. **`STEP 3: TAKE THE MINIMUM OF THREE SUB-RESULTS.`**
### **RECURSIVE SOLUTION :- T.L.E. (Not Accepted)**
```
// Recursive Code
class Solution {
public:
    int editDist(string &w1, string &w2, int n, int m){
        if(n == 0)                          // Base Case 1 : If first string is empty, simply return second string len. Because, we need atleast second
            return m;                       //               string size or len to convert first into second
        else if(m == 0)
                return n;                   // Base Case2 2: Vice-Versa of above base case
        else if(w1[n - 1] == w2[m - 1])
               return editDist(w1, w2, n - 1, m - 1); //  when both characters are matched don't need to do any operations 
        else               
            return 1 + min({editDist(w1, w2, n, m - 1), editDist(w1, w2, n - 1, m), editDist(w1, w2, n - 1, m - 1)});  // When characters Doesn't match 
    }                                                                                                          // we need to do Three Operations as 
    int minDistance(string word1, string word2) {                                                          // Mentioned Above & Take the minimum of them
        int n = word1.size(), m = word2.size();
        return editDist(word1, word2, n, m);
    }
};
```
**TIME COMPLEXITY : `O(3^N)`, Where, `N = (m + n)`, n : size of word1 & m  : size of word2** 
**SPACE COMPLEXITY : `O(constant)`, ignoring recusrion stack**
```
```
### **DP SOLUTION: TOP-DOWN OR MEMOIZATION (Accepted)**
* **Runtime : 10ms**
```
// Memoized Code (Top-Down)
class Solution {
public:
    int editDist(string &w1, string &w2, int n, int m, vector<vector<int>>& memo){
        if(n == 0)
            return m;
        if(m == 0)
                return n;
        if(memo[n][m] != -1)
            return memo[n][m];
        if(w1[n - 1] == w2[m - 1]){
            memo[n][m] = editDist(w1, w2, n - 1, m - 1, memo); //  when both characters are matched don't need to do any operations
            return memo[n][m];
        }
        else{               // When characters Doesn't match we need to do Three Operations as Mentioned Above & Take the minimum of them
            memo[n][m] = 1 + min({editDist(w1, w2, n, m - 1, memo), editDist(w1, w2, n - 1, m, memo), editDist(w1, w2, n - 1, m - 1, memo)});
            return memo[n][m];
        }
    }
    int minDistance(string word1, string word2) {
        int n = word1.size(), m = word2.size();
        vector<vector<int>> memo(n + 1, vector<int> (m + 1, -1));
        return editDist(word1, word2, n, m, memo);
    }
};
```
**TIME COMPLEXITY : `O(n * m)`, Where, n : size of word1 & m  : size of word2** 
**SPACE COMPLEXITY : `O(n * m)`, For using 2D array Aux space & Again, ignoring recusrion stack**
```
```
### **DP SOLUTION: BOTTOM-UP OR TABULATION (Accepted)**
* **Runtime : 4ms**
```
// Tabulation Code (Bottom-Up)
class Solution {
public:
    int minDistance(string w1, string w2) {
        int n = w1.size(), m = w2.size();
        vector<vector<int>> dp(n + 1, vector<int> (m + 1, 0));
        for(int i = 0; i <= n; ++i)     // Base Case 1:
            dp[i][0] = i;

        for(int j = 0; j <=m; ++j)      // Base Case 2: 
            dp[0][j] = j;

        for (int i = 1; i <= n; ++i) {
            for (int j = 1; j <= m; ++j) {
                if(w1[i - 1] == w2[j - 1])          //  when both characters are matched don't need to do any operations
                    dp[i][j] = dp[i - 1][j - 1];
                else                               // When characters Doesn't match we need to do Three Operations as Mentioned Above & Take the minimum of them
                    dp[i][j] = 1 + min({dp[i][j - 1], dp[i - 1][j], dp[i - 1][j - 1]});
            }
        }
        return dp[n][m];
    }
};
```
**TIME COMPLEXITY : `O(n * m)`, Where, n : size of word1 & m  : size of word2** 
**SPACE COMPLEXITY :  `O(n * m)`, For using 2D array Aux space**

