# Dynamic Programming (Tabulation) with Space Optimization:
# Approach
The function spacopti is used to find the minimum edit distance using dynamic programming (tabulation) with space optimization.
It initializes two vectors curr and next to store intermediate results during the computation.
The next vector is pre-filled with values representing the minimum number of operations needed to transform the suffix of string b into an empty string (i.e., characters are deleted).
Tabulation Loop:

The tabulation loop iterates over the indices of a and b from the end to the beginning.
It computes the minimum edit distance for each pair of substrings a[i:] and b[j:], storing the result in the curr vector.
The curr vector is updated iteratively as the loop progresses.
Matching Characters:

If the characters at a[i] and b[j] are the same, the function updates the ans variable with the value from next[j+1]. This represents the minimum edit distance for the remaining substrings a[i+1:] and b[j+1:].
Mismatching Characters:

If the characters at a[i] and b[j] are different, the function calculates three possible operations (insertion, deletion, and replacement) and updates the ans variable with the minimum value among them.
Space Optimization:

Instead of using two separate vectors for curr and next, the function uses only curr for tabulation. The next vector is effectively replaced by curr in each iteration, updating the values accordingly.
Output:

The minDistance function returns the result of the dynamic programming (tabulation) function spacopti(word1, word2), which represents the minimum number of operations required to transform word1 into word2.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:0(N*N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:0(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# CODE
```
class Solution {
public:

int spacopti(string& a, string& b)
{
    vector<int>curr(b.length()+11,0);
    vector<int>next(b.length()+111,0);
    for(int j =0;j<b.length();j++)
    {
        next[j]=b.length()-j;
    }


    for(int i=a.length();i>=0;i--)
    {
        for(int j = b.length();j>=0;j--)
        {
            int ans=0;
            curr[b.length()]=a.length()-i;
            if(a[i]==b[j])
            {
                ans= next[j+1];
            }
            else
            {
                int insert= 1 + curr[j+1];
                int deleteans= 1 + next[j];
                int replace= 1 + next[j+1];
                ans = min(insert , min(deleteans , replace));
            }
            curr[j]=ans;
        }
        next=curr;
    }
    return next[0];
}

    int minDistance(string word1, string word2) {
        return spacopti(word1,word2);

    }
};
```
# Recursive Function with Memoization:
# Approach


The function solve is a recursive function that takes two strings a and b, along with two indices i and j, representing the current position in a and b.
The function calculates the minimum distance (number of operations) required to transform the substring a[i:] into the substring b[j:].
The function uses memoization to store the results of subproblems in a 2D dp array. The dp array is used to avoid redundant calculations for overlapping subproblems.
Base Cases:

If the index i reaches the end of string a, the remaining characters in b need to be inserted to match a, so the function returns b.length() - j.
If the index j reaches the end of string b, the remaining characters in a need to be deleted to match b, so the function returns a.length() - i.
Memoization:

The function checks if the result for the current subproblem (i.e., solve(a, b, i, j, dp)) is already calculated and stored in the dp array. If so, it returns the stored result, avoiding redundant calculations.
Matching Characters:

If the characters at a[i] and b[j] are the same, no operation is required, so the function calls itself with i+1 and j+1.
Mismatching Characters:

If the characters at a[i] and b[j] are different, the function considers three possible operations (insertion, deletion, and replacement) and calculates the minimum distance by recursively calling itself with different indices and adding one for the operation performed.
Main Function:

The minDistance function initializes the dp array with -1 and calls the recursive function solve with the two strings word1 and word2, along with initial indices 0 and 0.
Output:

The minDistance function returns the minimum number of operations required to transform word1 into word2.
