This solution involves a little bit of math. We get a 0 at the end of multiplication, when we multiplying multiple of 2 & 5.
eg: 2 * 5 = 10
4 * 5 =20
2 * 15 =30
4 * 10 =40
This means we hae to figure out how many multiples  5's and 2's are there in the multiplication.
Suppose the number of multiples of 5's is x and 
the number of multiples of 2's is y.
So the number of trailing 0's would be min(x,y)
But in case of a factorials the multiples of 5 will always be less than multiples of 2.
eg n =12
multiples of 2 (y) = [2,4,6,8,10,12] = 6
multiples of 5 (y) = [5,10] = 2
So we only need to find y.

Below is the recursive solution for that.
```
class Solution {
    public int trailingZeroes(int n) {
        if (n/5 >= 5) {
            return n/5 + trailingZeroes(n/5);
        } else {
            return n/5;
        }  
    }
}
```

