The main idea - you need to figure out, how many 5's you have on n! multipliers. For example: 10 is 5 * 2, so there is one 5. 250 is 5 * 5 * 5 * 2, so there is three 5's. For every 5 you can find 2's in n! multipliers, and 5*2 will give you 10 and one zero in final result. So you don't need to find 2's, only 5's.

So, O(NlogN) solution solution first, it's easier to understand
```
var trailingZeroes = function(n) {
    let count = 0;
	// find 5's in k
	// return 1 for 10 and 3 for 250 from example;
    function getMaxPov5(k) {
        let max = 0;
        while ((k / 5) % 1 === 0) {
            max++;
            k /= 5;
        }
        return max;
    }
	// check only multipliers we can divide by 5
    for (let i = 5; i <= n; i += 5) {
        count += getMaxPov5(i);
    }
    return count;
};
```
