solutions.content:
Factorial of an integer (n) is obtained simply by multiplying of the numbers from 1 upto n (including n).

Its obvious that trailing zeros in any number are because of multiplication by 10. 

Similarly, While calculating a factorial, If the number gets multiplied by 10 or prime factors whose products is 10, then it will add a trailing zero at the end. 

Eg: factorial of 6 is 720. (1 trailing zeros).

*6! = 1 * 2 * 3 * 4 * 5 * 6
	= 1 * 2 * 3 * (2 * 2) * 5 * (2 * 3)*

In the above prime factors of numbers multiplied in the factorial, we can observe that there are 2s and 5s. Its clear that 2* 5 = 10.  So the combination of 2s and 5s are bringing in all the trailing zeros. 

Hence, 
    *number of trailing zeros 
			= min (number of 2s in prime factors, number of 5s in prime factors)*

Now, it is clear that all even numbers have a factor 2 but only multiples of 5 like 5, 10, 15, etc.. have a factor 5. So it is clear  that there are more number of 2 than 5 in any set of prime factors of factorial.

So the number of 5s will be the obvious minimum which is rather easy to count and may not require complete factorization as such.

For that, simply count the numbers divisible by 5 from 1 to n. There are some numbers which are multiples of higher powers of 5 and hence have more than one 5s in the prime factors. For that, we can count the numbers that are divisible by each higher powers of 5 upto  n. 
In summary,

*Number of 5s in the prime factors 
= Count of numbers divisible by 5 + Count of numbers divisible by 25 + Count of numbers divisible by 125 + ...
= floor(n/5) + floor(n/25) + floor(n/125) + floor(n/625) + ... until the number inside paranthesis gets to zero.*


Its simple Java Solution would be as follows: 

```
class Solution {
    public int trailingZeroes(int n) {

        int countZeros=0;

        while(n>0)
        {
            countZeros += n/5;
            n/=5; 
        }

        return countZeros;
    }
}
```

