solutions.content:
# Intuition
Like implementing RSA encryption

# Approach
Use least significant bit first/most significant bit first algorithm  to compute the modular exponentiation. And use the Euler-Fermat Theorem to reduce exponent number modulo phi(n). 
**Euler-Fermat Theorem:**
$$
a^{\phi(n)}\equiv 1 \pmod{n}
$$
for $\gcd(a, n)=1$.

In this problem, 
$$n=1337=(191)(7), \phi(n)=(191-1)(7-1)=(190)(6)=1140.$$

 What if $\gcd(a, n)\not=1$?
 That will be the boundary case. Try these 2 test cases: 
```
7
[1,1,4,0]
191
[1,1,4,0]
```
You will find Euler-Fermat Theorem not enough! Suppose $\gcd(a, p)=1$ & $\gcd(a, q) \not=1 $,  one can still use $a^{p-1} \equiv 1 \pmod{p}$ to deal with. Then the Chinese Remainder Theorem comes to play.

Chinese Remainder says:
Let $x\equiv x_i \pmod{n_i}$ with pairwise coprime $n_i$. Let $n=\prod_i n_i$ Then 
$$
x \equiv \sum_i x_iM_is_i \pmod{n}
$$
where $M_i=n/n_i, s_i\equiv M_i^{-1}\pmod{n_i}$ 

In our case:
$$
7^{-1}\pmod{191}\equiv 82, \ 191^{-1}\pmod{7}\equiv 4
$$

In fact Euler-Fermat Theorem is the basis for RSA. It can prove with the aid of Chinese Remainder the following theorem
# Therem. If an postive integer a<n Then a^{k*phi(n)+1} =a (mod n) on matter what gcd(a, n) is.

In other word, the function $f(x)=a^x\pmod{n}$ is a periodic function with $f(x)=f(x+k\phi(n))$ which quarantees RSA works!

