# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
 Utilize modular exponentiation and Euler's theorem to efficiently calculate the superpower.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Use recursive approach:
If the exponent array b is empty, return 1 (base case).
Otherwise, pop the last digit from b and call the function recursively for the remaining digits.
For each recursive call:
Take modulo MOD of the base a.
Calculate the superpower recursively for the remaining digits by raising it to the power of 10.
Apply the popped digit as an exponent to the base a, and take modulo MOD.
The final result is the product of the recursive superpower with exponent 10 and the separate exponentiation of the base a with the popped digit as exponent, both taken modulo MOD
# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n log n)
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)
# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    const int MOD = 1337;

    int power(int x, int n) {
        if (n == 0) return 1;
        x %= MOD;
        if (n % 2 == 1) return (x * power(x, n - 1)) % MOD;
        int half = power(x, n / 2);
        return (half * half) % MOD;
    }

    int superPow(int a, vector<int>& b) {
        if (b.empty()) return 1;

        a %= MOD;
        int last_digit = b.back();
        b.pop_back();
        return (power(superPow(a, b), 10) * power(a, last_digit)) % MOD;
    }
};

```

