**!! Intro-Algo-Optimization. Read till last for better understanding. !!**
```
class Node {
    boolean end;
    Node[] nodeArray;
    Node(){
        end=false;
        nodeArray=new Node[26];
    }
}
class Solution {
    Node root;
    public List<String> findAllConcatenatedWordsInADict(String[] words) {
        List<String> result=new ArrayList<String>();
        if(words.length<=2) return result;
        root=new Node();

        Arrays.sort(words,(a,b) -> a.length()-b.length());

        for(String s : words){
			if(s.isEmpty()) continue;
		/*words[] is sorted in asc order of length. So all the words inserted in 
        TRIE are of length <= s.length() . As all strings in words[] are unique and 
        as we did not insert 's' already , if 's' can be formed then it 
		means it was formed by concatenating two or more smaller words.
		*/
            if(isPossible(s,0)) result.add(s);
            else insert(s);
        }

        return result;
    }

    private boolean isPossible(String s,int index){
        if( index==s.length() ) return true;

        Node curr=root;
        for(int i=index,n=s.length() ; i<n ; i++){
            curr=curr.nodeArray[ s.charAt(i)-'a' ];
            if(curr==null) return false;
            //Found a word, now check if rest of the string can be formed.
            if(curr.end && isPossible(s,i+1))
                    return true;
        }
        return false;
    }

    private void insert(String s){
        Node curr=root;
        for(int i=0,n=s.length() ; i<n ; i++){
            int c=s.charAt(i)-'a';
            if(curr.nodeArray[c]==null) curr.nodeArray[c]=new Node();
            curr=curr.nodeArray[c];
        }
        curr.end=true;
    }
}
```
**What is TRIE ?** An efficient DS for info re**Trie**val
parameters : Boolean end, Node[] nodeArray.
The main use of TRIE is to maintain dictionary , as after each character there are two choices
i. any of the 26 characters [assuming loweraser]. node_array[char-'a'] will again form a TRIE.
ii.or nothing i.e., current char is the last character of word. For this case we maintain boolean parameter 
called end and end=true.

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/911df49e-c5b1-4a65-a8e9-c4bacb4affd9_1619610645.5904534.png)

 If you follow ROOT to a red circle then you can find a word. To represent red circles in TRIE 'end' parameter of node is used.
 We can see that common prefix is stored only once[ like for their,there..the is stored only once] and to insert or delete or search a word it on takes O(length of the word) , in english longest word is of 45char so typically to search/store all the words in english dictionary time complexity will be N* O(45) = N* O(1), but space complexity might be a issue here.

**Algo:**
1.Intially add all words into TRIE. 
2.For a word to be concatenated it should comprise entirely of at least two shorter words. 
FOR each word in dict
....FOR i = 0 to n-2 in word
check if at word[i] in TRIE has end=true, then check if the rest of that string can be formed .

**Optimization:**
For Step1 in algo, it takes N x O(L) = 10^7 in worst case.
Again for Step2 in algo, we are checking for each char in each word so again  N x O(L) = 10^7 operations. 
***So how can we improve time complexity ?***
We know that a bigger word requires smaller word to concatenate. So first insert smaller words first and check if a bigger word can be formed. 
-If, bigger word (b1) can be formed then no need to insert the bigger word again. By doing this we can save O(L) time to insert and O(L) space to insert.  Previously we took O(L) time to insert and O(L) to search, but now if the bigger word can be concatenated then no need to insert.

***How to implement ?***
-Sort words[] in ascending order of length.
-Now before inserting a word , check it can be concatenated by previously inserted words. If Yes, then no need to insert this bigger word thereby saving us O(L)-Time,space . Else, insert this word.

## **Approach 2 : DFS**
Same optimized approach can be applied to DFS with hashset.
**Algo:**
1.Sort  words[] in ascending order of length.
2.Now before inserting a word , check it can be concatenated by previously inserted words. If Yes, then no need to insert this bigger word thereby saving us time,space . Else, insert this word.

```
class Solution {
    HashSet<String> set = new HashSet<>();
    public List<String> findAllConcatenatedWordsInADict(String[] words) {
        List<String> result=new ArrayList<String>();
        if(words.length<=2) return result;

        Arrays.sort(words,(a,b) -> a.length()-b.length());

        for(String s : words){
            if(s.isEmpty()) continue;
            if(isPossible2(s)) result.add(s);
            else set.add(s);
        }

        return result;
    }

    private boolean isPossible2(String s){
        if(s.isEmpty()) return true;
        for(int i=1;i<=s.length();i++)
            if(set.contains(s.substring(0,i)) && isPossible2(s.substring(i)) )
                return true;
        return false;
    }
}
```

**Comparison :**
Trie approach - 44ms, DFS+HashSet - 275ms. Here Trie is faster.
**Trie**
-Insertion takes exactly O(L) time.
-For search, if word exists in dictionary then O(L) else less than that.
-As common prefix needs to be stored only once this saves memory also..

 **HashSet:**
 In ideal scenario insert and search should be O(1). A perfect hash function should evenly distribute N elements among N buckets, so that by calculating hash value we can retrieve from the respective bucket in O(1).
 But in reality it is not the case, we have to handle collisions. If they are many collisions then lookup time may even become O(N).
 -One more point to be noted, if hashmap is 75% full then it doubles the size,  rehashes and inserts all the data again. So if we are trying to store and lookup large dictionary hashmap may not be ideal.
 -Moreover we are checking if [i=1 to L] s.substring(0,i) is present in dictionary , so it my take L* LookUptime. Ideally LookUpTime=k=1 but 1<=k<=N . And we are repetaing this process for N strings. 
 So overall T(N) = N* L* K.

 Luckily after Java8, if they are many collision in hashmap bucket then it converts linear linking to a self balancing tree which reduces lookup time to Log(N) , still Log(N) > 1. 

**Hope this post was useful. Happy Coding :)**

