Almost all Trie solutions for this question TLE (time limit exceeded). The only Trie solution I could find that gets around TLE is by @mavs0603 here: https://leetcode.com/problems/concatenated-words/discuss/432417/Java-DFS-%2B-Trie

That solution works differently to my own, but I have used it to understand how to get around the TLE for my own solution.

Please provide corrections in the comments & I will gladly amend any mistakes.

```
// Break down of complexities per operation:
// sort input: O(n log n) time where n is number of words
// time & space for building trie: O(n*m) where m is length of word
// find if a word is concatenated: O(n*2^m)

// Overall:
// O(n*2^m) time where n is number of words, m is length of word.
// O(n*m) space for trie itself (probably higher due to recursive calls, but not sure what it is exactly)
public static List<String> findAllConcatenatedWordsInADict(String[] words) {
        List<String> res = new ArrayList<>();
        if (words == null || words.length < 2) {
            return res;
        }

		// sort words in ascending order
		// this way for an input like ["aaaaaaaaaa", "aaaaaaaa", "aa", "a"]
		// we don't actually bother inserting the largest words if they are concatenated
		// this is what helps the solution not TLE for the recent test case
        Arrays.sort(words, (a, b) -> a.length() - b.length());

        TrieNode root = new TrieNode('#');

		// Building our trie upfront can cause TLE for the most recent test case
		// That said one could uncomment the below line, then comment out the Arrays.sort() & the insert() operation
		// doing so would pass all sane test cases (44/45 would pass, with the final one producing a TLE)
        // buildTrie(words, root);

        for (String word : words) {
			// In order to avoid TLE (time limit exceeded) we process large words last (we have sorted the input)
			// So if a large word is concatenated (the first, smallest word, is never concatenated), it isn't added to the trie
			// We can instead build the trie upfront (I have commented that portion out) and not bother with sorting the input
			// But due to a recently added test case on LC this would cause TLE
			// The caveat, or interesting thing, about not building the trie upfront is 
			// that if later, larger, words are repeated versions of a prior concatenation - or comprised of prior concatenations
			// e.g input = ["abcd", "abcd", "abcdabcd", "abcdabcdabcd"] - our last word is either 3x"abcd" or "abcdabcd" + "abcd"
			// we do not/cannot use the prior concatenated words to determine if the later word is also concatenated/comprised of them
			// this is because all prior concatenated words are never inserted into the trie
			// instead, we have to use the smaller words to determine the if the later word is concatenated
			// for the given example, if we do not build the trie upfront, we would determine that yes, 
			// "abcdabcdabcd" is concatenated - it is made up of "abcd" + abcd" + abcd"
			// If we build the trie upfront, so insert all words into the trie, then we would be able to determine that
			// either/both "abcd" + abcd" + abcd" &  "abcdabcd" + "abcd" are concatenations of "abcdabcdabcd"
			// this is because all the words will exist in the trie
			// Additionally, building the trie upfront means we do not have to modify (sort) the input
            if (isConcatenated(0, 0, word, root)) {
                res.add(word);
            } else {
				// if you build the trie upfront you can comment this out:
                insert(word, root);
            }
        }

        return res;
    }

    private static void insert(String word, TrieNode root) {
        if (word == null || word.length() == 0) {
            return;
        }

        TrieNode temp = root;
        for (int i = 0; i < word.length(); i++) {
            char ch = word.charAt(i);
            if (!temp.children.containsKey(ch)) {
                temp.children.put(ch, new TrieNode(ch));
            }

            temp = temp.children.get(ch);
        }

        temp.isEndOfWord = true;
    }

    private static boolean isConcatenated(int j, int count, String word, TrieNode root) {
        if (count >= 2 && j == word.length()) {
			// Our current word is built up of 2 or more other words from the input (in the trie)
			// and the current word has been fully explored (j == length)
            return true;
        }

        TrieNode node = root;
        for (int i = j; i < word.length(); i++) {
            char ch = word.charAt(i);
            if (!node.children.containsKey(ch)) {
                return false;
            }

            node = node.children.get(ch);

            if (node.isEndOfWord && isConcatenated(i + 1, count + 1, word, root)) {
                return true;
            }
        }

        return false;
    }

    private static void buildTrie(String[] words, TrieNode root) {
        for (String word : words) {
            if (word == null || word.length() == 0) {
                continue;
            }

            TrieNode temp = root;
            for (int i = 0; i < word.length(); i++) {
                char ch = word.charAt(i);
                if (!temp.children.containsKey(ch)) {
                    temp.children.put(ch, new TrieNode(ch));
                }

                temp = temp.children.get(ch);
            }

            temp.isEndOfWord = true;
        }
    }

    private static class TrieNode {

        public TrieNode(char ch) {
            character = ch;
            isEndOfWord = false;
            children = new HashMap<>();
        }

        Map<Character, TrieNode> children;
		// this isn't used but it's helpful for debugging/stepping through
        char character;
        boolean isEndOfWord;
    }

// No idea if this is helpful for anyone, but adding it anyway:

// For the time complexity of O(n*2^n) it helped me to think of the input ["a", "a", "aaab"]:
// for "aaab" we would do a lot of unnecessary exploration/recursion to ultimately find out it isn't a concatenated word
// this is because "a" is in the trie & "a".isEndOfWord=true
// so for the first 3 characters we would recursively call isConcatenated(i + 1, count + 1, "aaab", root)
// once we get to the last/deepest level of recursion and reach "b"
// we determine that "aaab" is not a concatenated word afterall
// and each level of previous recursion where we encountered an "a"
// does another loop iteration before determining the next character also doesn't yield a concatenated word. 

// More detailed brain debug:
// For isConcatenated(0, 0, "aaab", root) we loop over entire "aaab"
// In the first loop iteration we find "a" is both in the trie & isEndOfWord=true
// thus we recurse & pass in (i+1) - each level of recursion explores letters after the current one
// inside our recursive call we find another "a" (i=1 at this point) & so recurse again
// This continues to happen until the very last "a" when i=2
// we recurse for this last "a" and pass in i+1, so i=3 at our last depth of recursion
// for this level of recursion we find that "b" isn't a child letter of our root node, so we return false
// Now we exit back up to our "a" & i=2 recursive level (and remember at this level our current trie node is "a", not root)
// This level of recursion continues in it's for loop & i goes to 3
// we now explore "b" again, but at a different/the current level of recursion
// we return false as "b" isn't a child of "a" and for every previous level of recursion where we encountered "a"
// we explore for another iteration in the same way:
// "aa" (i=1) would explore the next "a" during it's next loop iteration
// because the node variable (TrieNode object) is now "a" for each level of recursion & not root
// and "a" in the trie has no children, each level of recursion's next iteration would return false
// up another level of recursion we had "a" (i=0) & this would explore the next "a" which also returns false (same as "aa" case)
// As you can see, we do all this extra work even though the word "aaab" isn't a concatenated word
