# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Intuition is pretty simple.. Try to partition each word at each index and check every partitions are present in words vector. If it is then push it in ans vector and at the end return it.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Sort the words vector so that we can find any word within log(n) time.
2. Take every word and recursively do partition on each index and check if the both partition (before and after index) are present in word vector. 
3. for example: `words = [ "cat", "dog", "s", "catsdog" ]`
   and we are checking for `s = "catsdog"`

   So run a loop from 0 to s.size() and make partition on each index.
   - At first the left partition="c" and right parition="atsdog"
        - Check left partition is present in words vector..
        it's not present. So continue this process..
   - Repeat the process untill left partition="cat" and right partition="sdog".
        - Now left partition is present in word vector (use binary search for finding).
        - As left partition is present so we will check if the right partition is also present or not.. 
        - If it is then we will directly return true and if it is not then call the function for right partition to do the same. 

    - For this example the right partition "sdog" is not present in word vector. so `f("sdog")` call will go.

    - Now like before again a loop will run from 0 to s.size() and make partition on each index. At first the left partition="s" and right parition="dog".
        - Now left partition is present in word vector and we will now check if right partition is present or not. 
        - Here both partition is present so we will return true.

    - And in the end if it returns true then we will push the string to ans vector and return the ans vector finally.

# Complexity
- `Time complexity: O(nllog(n))`. where `n` is the number of words in the input vector, and `l` is the length of the longest word in the input vector.
The sorting of the input vector takes `O(nlog(n))` time.
For each word in the input vector, the function is_concatenated() is called, which takes `O(l)` time to check each substring of the word and check if it exists in the input vector using the is_present() function, which takes `O(log(n))` time as it uses binary search to check the presence of a word in the input vector.
So, the total time complexity is O(nlog(n)) + O(nllog(n)) = O(nllog(n)).

- `Space complexity: O(n)`. Ignoring recursion stack space.

