# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
For each word, we'll check if it's concatenated recursively. Check each word in the list to compute the return list.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
1. Duplicate the input array as a set because we'll be checking for containment a lot and will benefit from the constant lookup time.
2. Create a helper function to evaluate a single word. It will have a second paramter `allowSelf` so that on initial call, it will not return `true` on the basis of the word matching itself. For recursive calls tho, some prefix portion will have already matched and the remainder should be allowed to match itself, hence `allowSelf = true` in the recursive call.
3. Iterate through the list and append all concatenated words to the `res`.

# Complexity
$$L$$ is the length of the words (average for average, longest for worst case), $$N$$ is the number of words
- Time complexity: $$O(L^3 * N)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(N * L)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
    fun findAllConcatenatedWordsInADict(words: Array<String>): List<String> {
        // make a set for constant lookup time
        val wordBank = words.toSet()

        // define a recursive helper function that checks if a word is concatenated
        fun isConcatenated(word: String, allowSelf: Boolean): Boolean {
            if (allowSelf && word in wordBank) return true
            var isConc = false
            for (i in 1 until word.length) {
                if (word.substring(0, i) in wordBank) {
                    isConc = isConc || isConcatenated(word.substring(i), true)
                }
            }
            return isConc
        }

        var res = mutableListOf<String>()
        for (word in words) {
            if (isConcatenated(word, false)) {
                res.add(word)
            }
        }
        return res
    }
}
```

