solutions.content:
**HashSet and Backtracking Solution**
My original intuition was to use a trie, but this does not save you from iterating through each character unless you maintain word length within the Trie. It seemed like unnecessary overhead to me, so I did this with a HashSet and it still passed.
My Time complexity: O(nk^2), where n = number of words, k = length of each word
My Space complexity: O(n) as I maintain an extra Set for O(1) contains() method invocation

Please let me know your thoughts, I thought this was a much simpler solution than using a Trie but am here learning like everyone else so totally welcome to feedback!

```
private Set<String> seen;
    public List<String> findAllConcatenatedWordsInADict(String[] words) {
        seen = new HashSet(List.of(words));
        List<String> concat = new ArrayList();
        for(String word : words)
            if(backtrack(word, 0)) concat.add(word);
        return concat;
    }

    private boolean backtrack(String word, int count){
        //Base case: can have more than two concatenated words and still be valid but cannot have extraneous chars
		if(word.length() == 0 && count >=2) return true;
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder();
        for(int i = 0; i < word.length(); i++){
            sb.append(word.charAt(i));
            if(seen.contains(sb.toString()) && backtrack(word.substring(i+1), count+1)) return true;
        }
        return false;
    }
```

